When deciding on your subject--the part of your picture that needs to be in crystal clear focus--make sure you look at the areas in front of and beyond the subject. These are the areas that will be out of focus in your picture. Bokeh is a term used to refer to the blur of the picture. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e9/Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e9/Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-2Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The background should be a complimentary or contrasting color to your subject for optimal visual impact. A green field behind a red barn is an example of good contrast. The green in the field is going to blur out and give you a green backdrop for your subject. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d1/Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d1/Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-2Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The aperture on a lens refers to the "eye" of the camera. The lens aperture is similar to the pupil of an eye. If it is dark outside, your pupil will dilate. The same holds true for your lens aperture. This is also referred to as the f-stop setting. The higher the f-stop number, the smaller the aperture. The smaller the f-stop number, the larger the aperture. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ac/Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ac/Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Try stopping down to a larger aperture, which means a smaller f-number. You can try starting with f/2.8. The lower your f-stop number, the shorter your DOF is going to be. The higher the f-number, such as f/22, the more of the picture will be in focus. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/09/Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/09/Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Achieve-Depth-of-Field-in-Photography-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
